The single biggest example of law in Indian history is the landmark case of Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973).This single judgment saved the democratic framework of India by creating the "Basic Structure Doctrine," ensuring that no government could ever misuse its power to turn India into a dictatorship.🇮🇳 The Real-Life Story Behind the LawIn the early 1970s, the head of a Hindu monastery in Kerala, Swami Kesavananda Bharati, sued the state government because it tried to seize his land under new property management laws.The Power Struggle: At the same time, the central government under Prime Minister Indira Gandhi was passing constitutional amendments that essentially said: "Parliament has absolute power and can change any part of the Constitution, including taking away citizen rights."The Ultimate Showdown: The case escalated to the Supreme Court of India. To settle the debate over who held supreme power—the Parliament or the Constitution—the court assembled a 13-judge bench, the largest in Indian history.⚖️ The Landmark RulingThe judges debated for 68 days. In a nail-biting 7 to 6 majority vote, the Supreme Court delivered its verdict:Parliament does have the power to amend the Constitution, but it cannot touch or destroy its "Basic Structure."The Court ruled that the Constitution has certain foundational pillars that are sacred. These include:Democracy: The government must always be chosen by the people.Secularism: The state cannot favor one religion over another.Separation of Powers: The judiciary, legislature, and executive must keep each other in check.Judicial Review: The courts always retain the right to strike down unfair government laws.🌍 Why This is a "Big" Example of LawIt Saved Indian Democracy: Just two years later, in 1975, the government declared a national Emergency and suspended civil liberties. Because of the Basic Structure rule, the government could not permanently alter the Constitution to dissolve democracy.The Ultimate Check and Balance: It established that the Constitution is supreme, not the politicians ruling at any given time.Global Legal Blueprint: This uniquely Indian legal doctrine has since been studied and adopted by supreme courts in other countries—like Bangladesh, Pakistan, and Kenya—to protect their own democracies from authoritarian regimes.
